\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Wigglers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The purpose of a wiggler is to create a spatially periodic magnetic field.
 We have already seen two different configurations of wigglers.
 The first wiggler used in an operational FEL consists of a helical wire
 wrapped around an evacuated tube that is occupied by electrons and radiation.
 Current is passed through the helical wire and a magnetic arises due to
 the Biot-Savart law.
 From the Biot-Savart law we know the direction the magnetic field points
 is in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{B}\propto Id\mathbf{l}\times\mathbf{r}
\]

\end_inset

Alterntively we curl the fingers of our right hands around a section of
 wire and point our thumbs along the direction of the current.
 Imagining doing this with the helical wire pictured above, we see that
 the components of the magnetic field pointing along the direction of propagatio
n of the electrons cancel out and only the tranverse components, that is,
 the components pointing perpendicular to the direction of propagation,
 are left.
 Moreover, we see that in between windings, the magnetic field oscillates
 between pointing into the page and out of the page.
 If we do this more carefully, we see that the magnetic field rotates around
 the axis of propagation in a circular motion.
 The spatial period of this rotation is 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{u}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get an idea of the trajectory of the electron as it passes through the
 wiggler we simply note that the magnetic force on the electron is given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{F}_{M}=e(\mathbf{v\times}\mathbf{B})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know that the magnetic field of the helical wiggler oscillates between
 pointing into the page and out of the page.
 Suppose the electrons in the beam are travelling to the left.
 Then when the electron is in a region of the wiggler where the magnetic
 field is pointing into the page, we compute the cross product and see that
 the the force on the electron is pointing down.
 So in this region the electron will tend downwards.
 When the electron is in a region of the wiggler where the magnetic field
 is pointing out of the page, we compute the cross product again and see
 that the magnetic force on the electron is now pointing upwards, the opposite
 of before.
 Thus the electron experiences a 'wiggling' force and so its trajectory
 is correspondingly wiggly.
