\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Ponderomotive Wave
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ponderomotive force is the force an electron feels inside an oscillating
 electric field, like an electromagnetic wave.
 It can be thought of as the force the electron feels due to the intensity
 of light.
 As a reference, its form is given here for reference:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{F}_{p}=-\frac{e^{2}}{4m\omega}\nabla E^{2}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the mass of the electron, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is the angular frequency of oscillation of the electric field and 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is the amplitude of the electric field.
 Note that the intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the free electron laser, the radiation field of the light in the wiggler
 combines with the magnetic field of the wiggler by superposition.
 This combination is called the 
\series bold
ponderomotive wave
\series default
.
 The ponderomotive wave travels slower than the speed of light 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 This is because the magnetic field of the wiggler is constant in time and
 has no time evolution (
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{u}=0$
\end_inset

), while the light field has both a spatial evolution and a time evolution.
 Thus in the superposition of these waves, the resulting wave has a wavenumber
 that is equal to the sum of the wavenumbers of the two waves (
\begin_inset Formula $k+k_{u}$
\end_inset

) and the frequency is just the frequency of the light field (
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

).
 Thus the phase velocity of the ponderomotive wave is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, since:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{p}=\frac{\omega}{k+k_{u}}<\frac{\omega}{k}=c\qquad\text{where }k_{u}=\frac{2\pi}{\lambda_{u}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the ponderomotive wave is slower than 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, and since the electrons are relativistic, it is more than the plausible
 that the electrons can travel at the same speed and near the same speed
 as the ponderomotive wave.
 In addition to electrons travelling slower than the ponderomotive wave,
 there can be electrons that travel faster than it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Light Amplification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we match the speed of the electrons to close to the speed of the
 ponderomotive wave.
 We can do this because we know can know 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{u}$
\end_inset

 independently of the electrons and calculate what electron speed 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{e}$
\end_inset

 we want so that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{e}\approx v_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 The electrons feel the ponderomotive force due to the field of the ponderomotiv
e wave.
 This force pushes electrons away from the antinodes of the ponderomotive
 wave towards the nodes of the wave where the electrons can form bunches
 and travel with the wave in resonance.
 Electrons that are moving slightly faster than the ponderomotive wave are
 slowed down and lose kinetic energy.
 This kinetic energy goes to the wave and the wave is amplified.
 Electrons that are moving slightly slower than the ponderomotive wave are
 sped up and gain kinetic energy at the expense of the wave.
 Thus if the beam is mostly composed of electrons that are faster than the
 ponderomotive wave, then the wave will be steal energy from the electron
 beam and be amplified.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Emitted Wavelength
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand the wavelength that gets emitted we note that there are two
 phenomena at play in addition to the process of bremsstrahlung that the
 electron undergoes.
 The first is that the electrons are travelling close to the speed of light
 and so as they pass through the wiggler they experience a spatial magnetic
 period of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{u}/\gamma$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{u}$
\end_inset

 because of length contraction.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the relativistic factor and is given by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma=\Big(1+\frac{v^{2}}{c^{2}}\Big)^{-1/2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to the length contraction that the electrons experience, the
 light is emitted by a relativistic source and then measured in the lab
 frame.
 This means there will be a relativistic doppler shift, and we get a second
 factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equation that gives the value of the emitted wavelength, derived starting
 from Maxwell's equations and keeping in mind the relativistic phenomena,
 is given by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda=\frac{\lambda_{u}}{2\gamma^{2}}\Big(1+K^{2}\Big)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{2}$
\end_inset

 is called the strength parameter and characterizes the strength of the
 magnetic field of the wiggler.
 It is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K^{2}=\frac{1}{4\pi^{2}}\Big(\frac{\lambda_{u}^{2}r_{0}B^{2}}{mc^{2}}\Big)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the classical radius of the electron, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the strength of the magnetic field of the wiggler, and 
\begin_inset Formula $mc^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the rest energy of the electron.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 we see explicitly how free electron lasers are tuned.
 Normally 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are chosen during the design and construction of the free electron laser.
 Thus it is the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma mc^{2}$
\end_inset

 term that we control to tune the laser during normal operation.
 One can easily pick a desired wavelength 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and then calculate for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 required to emit the desired wavelength.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma=\sqrt{\frac{\lambda_{u}}{2\lambda}\Big(1+K^{2}\Big)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this one know the necessary speed of the electrons and the energy of
 the electrons.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Xray Free Electron Lasers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Free electron lasers can be tuned to many wavelengths but the hard Xray
 wavelengths (0.01 to 0.2nm) pose a special challenge.
 Mirrors for these wavelengths do not exist and so a cavity cannot be constructe
d.
 Without a cavity the light cannot be fed back into the wiggler for further
 amplification.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get around this, Xray free electron lasers are designed with extremely
 long wigglers that can reach the length of over a hundred meters (compare
 this to the 5.2m wiggler used in the first free electron laser).
 The question still remains, how does the light become coherent without
 a cavity?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
SASE Free Electron Lasers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mechanism of self-amplified spontaneous emission is what allows the
 xray radiation to be amplified and coherent.
 As an example we look at the operation of the free electron laser at the
 LCLS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The process begins with an ultraviolet pulse that bombards a copper plate.
 After each pulse hits the copper plate, a burst of electrons packed together
 into a bunch leave the copper plate and enter the accelerator.
 The electron bunches are accelerated and then enter the especially long
 wiggler.
 In the wiggler the electrons begin to emit xray radiation.
 The electrons travel with the radiation and amplify it by the mechanism
 described above.
 Moreover, the ponderomotive force pushes the electrons away from the antinodes
 of the radiation and the electrons in the bunches form thin sheets of electrons
 separated by the wavelength of the radiation.
 These are called microbunches.
 When the electrons are in microbunches they continue to emit radiation
 and because the electrons are equally spaced by the wavelength of radiation
 from each other the radiation they emit is in phase and coherent, and very
 intense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Bunch Compressors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As part of the acceleration stage of the electrons, the electrons go through
 a series of bunch compressors.
 Bunch compressors decrease the spacing between the bunches of electrons
 and in so doing can control the the duration of time between pulses.
 The bunch compressor (also called a chicane) works by introducing a slight
 s-curve in the path of the electrons.
 Much as an s-curve in a road, the electron bunch that reache the s-curve
 first must slow down to make the turn.
 This allows the electron bunches behind the first bunch to close the distance
 between the two.
 With careful tweaking the bunches after leaving the bunch compressor can
 be made to be closer together.
